      <div class="page-header-area">
        <h1 class="page-title">Tokens</h1>
        <p class="page-desc">Use design tokens as the single source of truth to define, scale, and implement every Prism design decision across endpoint experiences.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="main-content-area">
        <div class="main-content-inner">

          <!-- Intro -->
          <div class="doc-section" style="margin-top: 16px;">
            <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--prism-text-muted); max-width: 760px;">In Prism, tokens power consistency across dashboards, device inventory, patch workflows, security alerts, AI insights, policy builders, and remediation journeys. Tokens ensure that design choices are reusable, themeable, accessible, and engineering-ready across the full endpoint ecosystem.</p>
          </div>

          <hr class="doc-divider" />

          <!-- Token principles -->
          <div class="doc-section" id="token-principles">
            <h2 class="doc-section-title">Token principles</h2>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Four rules that govern how tokens are created, named, and used in Prism.</p>

            <div class="principles-grid">
              <div class="principle-item">
                <h3>1. Design decisions must be named</h3>
                <p>Every reusable design decision must become a token. Never store raw hex values, random px values, one-off shadows, local font sizes, custom border radii, or hardcoded z-index values. If it repeats, it becomes a token.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="principle-item">
                <h3>2. Tokens describe meaning, not appearance</h3>
                <p>Good: <code>color.background.danger.bold</code>, <code>space.200</code>, <code>font.heading.large</code>. Bad: <code>red-500</code>, <code>padding-16</code>, <code>font-24</code>. Names encode purpose, not visual output.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="principle-item">
                <h3>3. Use three-tier token architecture</h3>
                <p>Primitive tokens hold raw values. Semantic tokens alias primitives by meaning. Component tokens scope overrides per component. Each tier adds context without duplicating values.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="principle-item">
                <h3>4. Theme everything through modes</h3>
                <p>Every semantic token maps differently per theme. Never branch theme logic in component code. Let the token layer handle all theme resolution automatically.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Three-tier diagram -->
            <div style="margin-top: 32px;">
              <h3 id="three-tier" class="doc-h3">Three-tier architecture</h3>
              <div class="tier-diagram">
                <div class="tier-row">
                  <div class="tier-label" style="border-left: 3px solid var(--prism-violet);">Primitive Tokens</div>
                  <div class="tier-arrow">&rarr;</div>
                  <div class="tier-desc">Raw values: Grey-500, Cobalt-300, 16px, 400 weight</div>
                </div>
                <div class="tier-row">
                  <div class="tier-label" style="border-left: 3px solid var(--prism-fuchsia);">Semantic Tokens</div>
                  <div class="tier-arrow">&rarr;</div>
                  <div class="tier-desc">Meaning-based aliases: Text-Primary, BG-Success, Border-Error</div>
                </div>
                <div class="tier-row">
                  <div class="tier-label" style="border-left: 3px solid var(--prism-cyan);">Component Tokens</div>
                  <div class="tier-arrow">&rarr;</div>
                  <div class="tier-desc">Scoped overrides: Button/bg-primary, Input/border-focus</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <hr class="doc-divider" />

